[2] Possible H1N1
Date: Wed 22 May 2013
Source: AL.com [edited]
http://blog.al.com/montgomery/2013/05/one_of_the_deaths_in_unknown_r.html


One of the deaths in the recent outbreak of an unknown respiratory illness could be associated with the H1N1 flu virus. The Dothan Eagle, which is based in Houston County, is reporting that officials with the local office of the Alabama Department of Public Health said that one of the 2 deaths could be associated with the H1N1 virus.

The number of those infected has risen from 7 to 9, Lesa C. Smith, a registered nurse with the state Department of Public Health told the newspaper. The Department of Public Health, along with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, are investigating the illness, which they described as a "cluster of respiratory illnesses of unknown origin." According to the Associated Press, the CDC is expected to release more information about the illness on Thursday [23 May 2013]. Al.com requested comment from the CDC on Wednesday [22 May 2013] afternoon, but a message hasn't been returned.

The 2 deaths associated with the illness occurred Saturday and Sunday [18-19 May 2013], according to the Dothan Eagle. Some patients with the illness are improving and being allowed to return home. Smith told the Dothan Eagle that the 3 key symptoms of the illness are shortness of breath, coughing and fever. Two of the infected people tested positive for specific viruses, which included the H1N1 flu virus. Another person tested positive for the type A virus [H3N2?], which is a typical seasonal flu virus.

[Byline: Erin Edgemon]

