[In the USA, during the 1st week of May 2013, influenza activity continued to decrease since peaking in late December 2012 to early January 2013 and is now below seasonal thresholds. Nationally, the proportion of influenza-like illnesses (ILI) outpatient consultations decreased to 1.0 percent, below the national baseline of 2.2 percent. The proportion of clinical ILI specimens testing positive for influenza decreased from the peak of 38 percent in the last week of 2012 to 6.5 percent (177/2746) during the week ending April 2013. The proportion of all deaths attributed to pneumonia and influenza (P&I) reported through the 122 Cities Mortality Reporting System continued to decrease from the peak of 9.8 percent in the 4th week of January 2013 to 6.6 percent, which is below the threshold of 7.2 percent. Overall numbers of P&I deaths since the beginning of the season have been relatively high compared to recent seasons. Laboratory confirmed influenza related hospitalizations were 44.2 per 100 000 population; this was higher than the previous 3 seasons and was most notably in the age group over 65 years, accounting for 50 percent of all reported cases. Among all hospitalizations, 9757 (79.2 percent) were associated with influenza A and 2476 (20.1 percent) with influenza B.

Since the beginning of the 2012-13 influenza season, all influenza As were antigenically similar to the 2012-13 northern hemisphere vaccine viruses, although 0.3 percent (4/1268) of A(H3N2) and 1.3 percent (3/234) of A(H1N1)pdm09 viruses tested had reduced titres, with antiserum produced against the A/Victoria/361/2011 and A/California/7/2009 viruses, respectively. Of the influenza B viruses characterized, 33.0 percent (269/815) belonged to the B/Victoria/02/87-like lineage, which is not in the current trivalent vaccine.

A map of the state of Alabama showing Dothan in the southeast corner can be accessed at: http://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/USA/alabama_map.htm. - Mod.CP]

[One suspects that with the heightened awareness worldwide for severe acute respiratory illnesses [SARI], the occurrence of 7 apparent cases in a short period of time in a localized area raised an alarm to warrant immediate investigation, a positive sign of good disease surveillance activities. The identification of a combination of influenza A H1N1, rhinovirus and bacterial pneumonia explains the severity of the disease seen, as influenza A H1N1 has been associated with severe disease, and the addition of a secondary bacterial pneumonia in 3 cases adds to the severity of the clinical presentation.

This thread is now closed. - Mod.MPP

